  "text": "As with other responses, there appear to be interactions between the opiate and other systems in GI functions. Nonadrenergic, noncholinergic mechanisms were suggested for the modulation of opiate activation of circular muscle of the small intestine, because the potency of the effect of morphine was equivalent to that of vagal nerve stimulation [CITATION_1] . In the GI system of goldfish, Met-enkephalin counteracted the effect of serotonin (283), indicating involvement of both systems in its responses. There was probably opiate mediation of nitric aciddependent neurotransmission, because either Met-enkephalin or DADLE suppressed a portion of the inhibitory junction potential that was sensitive to arginine analogues (29).",
